Question: How can I read/write bits from/to a file in Java?: :I need to read file stream as bits and then I should be able to write bits to file again. Are there any classes for this purpose?
Please using this api: InputStream.read.
Answer: <<<api>>>: InputStream.read
<<<code>>>: 
```java
InputStream in = new FileInputStream("input.txt");
int bit;
while ((bit = in.read()) != -1) {
    // process bit
}
```
To write bits to a file, you can use a FileOutputStream and write the bits one by one.
```java
OutputStream out = new FileOutputStream("output.txt");
// suppose bits is an array of bits
for (int i = 0; i < bits.length; i++) {
    out.write(bits[i]);
}
```
<<<explanation>>>: 
The InputStream.read method reads the next byte of data from the input stream. The value byte is returned as an int in the range 0 to 255. If no byte is available because the end of the stream has been reached, the value -1 is returned.

To write bits to a file, we can use the OutputStream.write method. This method writes the specified byte to the output stream. The general contract for write is that one byte is written to the output stream for each call on the write method.

Note: The write method of OutputStream does not write a byte to the output stream. It writes the byte to the output stream and forces any buffered output bytes to be written out.

So, when we use write method of OutputStream, it writes the integer value as a byte to the file. If you want to write individual bits, you would need to manipulate the integer value to get the individual bits and write them one by one.

Also, remember to close the input and output streams after you are done with them to free up system resources.
```java
in.close();
out.close();
```
